Class GenericFrame

  • java.lang.Object
    • remixlab.dandelion.geom.Frame
      • remixlab.dandelion.core.GrabberFrame
        • remixlab.dandelion.branch.GenericFrame
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    GenericGrabber<Constants.MotionAction>, Grabber, Constants, Trackable, Copyable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    InteractiveFrame

    public class GenericFrame
extends GrabberFrame
implements GenericGrabber<Constants.MotionAction>, Copyable, Constants
    An interactive-frame is a GrabberFrame that implements the GenericGrabber interface. An interactive-frame implements the following actions on top of the grabber-frame gesture converting methods (such as GrabberFrame.gestureArcball(MotionEvent), GrabberFrame.gestureDrive(MotionEvent), etc): Constants.KeyboardAction, Constants.ClickAction, Constants.DOF1Action, Constants.DOF2Action, Constants.DOF3Action and Constants.DOF6Action. The GrabberScene.motionAgent() and the GrabberScene.keyboardAgent() provide high-level methods to define custom action bindings.

    An interactive-frame rotates either around the Eye.anchor() (e.g., Constants.DOF2Action.ROTATE, Constants.DOF6Action.HINGE), or its GrabberFrame.sceneUpVector() (e.g., Constants.DOF2Action.ROTATE_CAD). In the latter case, the GrabberFrame.sceneUpVector() defines a 'vertical' direction around which the camera rotates. The camera can rotate left or right, around this axis. It can also be moved up or down to show the 'top' and 'bottom' views of the scene. As a result, the GrabberFrame.sceneUpVector() will always appear vertical in the scene, and the horizon is preserved and stays projected along the camera's horizontal axis. Use Eye.setUpVector(Vec) to define the GrabberFrame.sceneUpVector() and align the camera before starting a Constants.DOF2Action.ROTATE_CAD action to ensure these invariants are preserved.

    See Also:
    MotionAgent, KeyboardAgent
